## Executive Summary

A Vulnerability Assessment and Penetration Testing (VAPT) engagement was conducted against a controlled laboratory target, Metasploitable2 (192.168.56.101), using the Penetration Testing Execution Standard (PTES) methodology. The objective of the assessment was to identify exposed services, discover security weaknesses, validate findings through manual analysis, and recommend remediation measures to improve the overall security posture of the target system.

The assessment was performed using Kali Linux, Nmap, Burp Suite, and OpenVAS. Reconnaissance activities identified multiple publicly accessible services including FTP, SSH, Telnet, HTTP, SMB, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and Apache Tomcat. Several services were found to be outdated and potentially vulnerable due to insecure configurations and legacy software versions.

Manual validation was conducted using Burp Suite to inspect web traffic and verify service accessibility. OpenVAS was used to perform automated vulnerability scanning and risk assessment. The findings indicated a large attack surface and multiple opportunities for unauthorized access if deployed in a production environment.

The engagement successfully demonstrated the complete VAPT lifecycle including reconnaissance, enumeration, vulnerability assessment, validation, reporting, and remediation planning. Appropriate security recommendations have been provided to reduce risk and improve system hardening.

